{
  "texts": [
    "Two of the models stand out from each category in current research [14].",
    "The discrete emotional model proposed by Ekman [45] describes discrete emotions as a group of universal or in other words as being commonly accepted in different cultures and determines 6 basic emotions namely anger, fear, sadness, joy, surprise, and disgust.",
    "On the other hand, the dimensional model defines emotions on two or three-dimensional planes.",
    "One of the widely known dimensional model is Russel's circumplex model [48] in which feelings of pleasant to unpleasant emotions are represented on a valance scale while feelings of being active and inactive are represented on an arousal scale.",
    "Thus, emotions are interpreted according to the values of each scale."
  ]
}